ANTHRAX - CANADA (09): (ALBERTA), BISON
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: 21 Aug 2015
Source: Fort McMurray Today [edited]
http://www.fortmcmurraytoday.com/2015/08/21/anthrax-kills-one-of-three-bison-at-syncrude-ranch


Three of Syncrude's famous Beaver Creek Wood Bison have been found dead, according to the company, and one is confirmed to have been infected with anthrax.

Syncrude said on Friday [21 Aug 2015] that it had found 3 dead bison within in the past 2 weeks near the ranch, which is located within Syncrude's Mildred Lake site. The most recent was found on Thursday, and tests completed Friday afternoon confirmed that it had contracted the bacteria. Spokesperson Leithan Slade says the company has since taken several steps, including isolating the remaining animals from the carcasses of the dead bison, restricting access to the ranch, and closing the public viewpoint located on Highway 63. "We're taking all necessary precautions to ensure the safety of our workers that care for the animals, and the animals themselves," Slade said.

Only one of the dead animals is confirmed to have been carrying the anthrax bacteria, as tests are still outstanding on the other 2. Slade says his company is still reviewing its next steps and will consider whether it can test the live animals for the bacteria.

For more than 20 years, the Beaver Creek Wood Bison herd -- now numbering approximately 300 -- have roamed across the Beaver Creek Wood Bison Ranch, spanning 500 hectares of reclaimed land north of Fort McMurray.

The ranch sits on top of a former open pit mine, and Syncrude has used it as an example that their reclamation efforts can support plants and animals native to Wood Buffalo. The project has been an enormous public relations victory for Syncrude. "Syncrude has always taken great pride in the health of our bison herd. It has become quite a success symbol for the company," Slade said. "At this point, it's kind of still too early to say whether (the deaths) will have an impact on the future of the herd."

In addition to the animal found on Thursday [20 Aug 2015], Slade says that one was found dead on Wednesday, and the other was found dead the week prior.

This is not the 1st case of anthrax killing a bison in Wood Buffalo this summer; in July 2015, 52 bison were killed from anthrax exposure in Wood Buffalo National Park. However, this is the 1st anthrax-related death of an animal in captivity the region has seen this summer [2015]. Slade says it's the 1st time the company has had a positive test for anthrax in any of its bison. He added the company doesn't yet know how the animals contracted the bacteria.

Anthrax can survive as a spore for decades underneath soil. Combined changes in soil moisture, from flooding and drying, can lead to a spore build-up on pastures. It is believed that after hot and dry periods, heavy rain can carry the spores into low areas that have bodies of water. The anthrax would then concentrate in the water, a fatal scenario for thirsty animals frequenting the area.

[Byline: Garrett Barry, Vincent McDermott]

