******
[2]
Date: 21 Aug 2015
Source: Edmonton Journal [edited]
http://www.edmontonjournal.com/Anthrax+confirmed+dead+bison+found+Syncrude+ranch+site/11308587/story.html


The body of a bull found Thursday [20 Aug 2015] was determined to have been infected with anthrax, Syncrude said in an email Friday. Two other bison were found dead earlier in the week. Test results are still pending in those cases. The Syncrude herd has not had a case of anthrax in the past, Slade said.

The carcasses were discovered in the main pasture of Syncrude's Beaver Creek Wood Bison Ranch, east of the North Mine. The area is not accessible to the public.

The ranch has been closed and so has a public viewpoint off Highway 63 where some bison from the 300-animal herd are kept during summer months. Other bison have been separated from the carcasses. A plan is being finalized for safe disposal of the dead bison.

In 1993, Syncrude and the Fort McKay First Nation relocated a small herd of wood bison from Elk Island National Park to a reclaimed area at Syncrude's Mildred Lake Mine site. The idea was to test the land's capability to support large mammals. Syncrude still manages the herd with the Fort McKay First Nation.

[Byline: David Howell]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Back in 1993, it was believed that the success of the project would help rebuild the shattered population of the wood bison, an animal with significant cultural importance to the local Metis and First Nations communities. It would also prove that the reclaimed land was sustainable, capable of supporting the same plants and animals that existed long before anyone began extracting Alberta's black gold to oil thirsty markets. Success meant a massive public relations victory for Syncrude.

Although he was already working as a mine maintenance manager for Syncrude, it was Jack Peden's job to use his knowledge as a cattle rancher to build a herd. The criteria were relatively simple, he says. The herd had to come from animals that were physically healthy, capable of breeding and purebred. A total of 6 mature cows, 15 male calves, and 9 female calves arrived at Syncrude on 16 Feb 1993, relocated from Elk Island National Park near Edmonton. "Once they got off that truck, they ran to the edges of the land and looked for a way out. They didn't know where they were," said Peden. "It took awhile for them to get used to the new land, and it was very challenging. Bison are different than other cattle species. They're a wild animal. These guys are big, very strong, and not easy to handle. You gotta use a lot of caution when handling them."

Today, the health of the animals is the responsibility of Fort McKay Environment LP. The bison are so healthy that the Calgary Zoo is interested in storing their genetic material, since Syncrude keeps detailed records of pedigree (extracted from: http://www.fortmcmurraytoday.com/2013/07/08/syncrude-celebrates-bison-ranch-anniversary).

This Beaver Creek Wood Bison Ranch is north of Fort McMurray and some distance from all other anthrax outbreaks this year (2015) in Alberta and the Northwest Territories; see: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fort_McMurray, which has a map showing Ft. McMurray in northwest Alberta. The origin of this outbreak has yet to be revealed. A key point will be the genetics of this recent outbreak, as the bison in the Wood Bison National Park and surrounding areas have their own specific strain, very different from that found in Albertan cattle. Off the cuff, the 1st thought is that there have been unappreciated wildlife anthrax outbreaks in northern Alberta this summer (2015) and maybe in previous years. And once it hit this small bison herd, it was obvious. We must await the knowledgeable opinions of the anthrax experts in AB & NT. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3597470,263.]
